# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: australia-women-s-national-cricket-team
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:australia-women-s-national-cricket-team/1973-women-s-cricket-world-cup] The **1973 Women's Cricket World Cup** was the inaugural Women's Cricket World Cup, held in England from 20 June to 28 July 1973.
[src:australia-women-s-national-cricket-team/1973-women-s-cricket-world-cup] It was the first tournament of its kind, held two years before the first limited overs World Cup for men in 1975.
[src:australia-women-s-national-cricket-team/1973-women-s-cricket-world-cup] The competition was won by the hosts, England.
[src:australia-women-s-national-cricket-team/1973-women-s-cricket-world-cup] The competition was the brainchild of businessman Sir Jack Hayward, who contributed £40,000 towards its costs.
[src:australia-women-s-national-cricket-team/1973-women-s-cricket-world-cup] England, Australia, New Zealand, Trinidad and Tobago and Jamaica were joined by an International XI and a Young England team in a round-robin league which saw the team with the most points win the World Cup.
[src:australia-women-s-national-cricket-team/1973-women-s-cricket-world-cup] England topped the group with 20 points from their six matches, including five victories and one defeat, while Australia were runners up posting 17 points with four wins.
[src:australia-women-s-national-cricket-team/1973-women-s-cricket-world-cup] The final round-robin match, held at Edgbaston on 28 July, was distinguished by a commanding century by Enid Bakewell of England, whose 118 formed the bedrock of England's imposing 279/3 in their 60 overs, with captain Rachael Heyhoe Flint scoring 64.
[src:australia-women-s-national-cricket-team/1973-women-s-cricket-world-cup] Australia were restricted by tight England bowling and fell well short of their target, scoring 187/9.
[src:australia-women-s-national-cricket-team/1973-women-s-cricket-world-cup] The cup was presented by Princess Anne and the winning England team were hosted at a reception at 10 Downing Street by Prime Minister Edward Heath.
[src:australia-women-s-national-cricket-team/1973-women-s-cricket-world-cup] Bakewell, one of England's finest all time players, was the leading run-scorer in the competition with 264 runs while Rosalind Heggs, of Young England, was the leading wicket-taker with 12 wickets.
[src:australia-women-s-national-cricket-team/1973-women-s-cricket-world-cup] The next World Cup was held five years later in 1978.
[src:australia-women-s-national-cricket-team/1978-women-s-cricket-world-cup] The **1978 Women's Cricket World Cup** was an international cricket tournament played in India from 1 to 13 January 1978.
[src:australia-women-s-national-cricket-team/1978-women-s-cricket-world-cup] Hosted by India for the first time, it was the second edition of the Women's Cricket World Cup, after the inaugural 1973 World Cup in England.
[src:australia-women-s-national-cricket-team/1978-women-s-cricket-world-cup] The World Cup was the first international cricket tournament hosted by India.
[src:australia-women-s-national-cricket-team/1978-women-s-cricket-world-cup] Only four teams participated, the lowest number in the tournament's history – Australia, England, India and New Zealand.
[src:australia-women-s-national-cricket-team/1978-women-s-cricket-world-cup] The teams played a round-robin tournament of three matches each, with Australia going undefeated to claim its first title.
[src:australia-women-s-national-cricket-team/1978-women-s-cricket-world-cup] Australia's captain, Margaret Jennings, led the tournament in runs, while her teammate, Sharyn Hill, led the tournament in wickets.
[src:australia-women-s-national-cricket-team/1978-women-s-cricket-world-cup] Three of the five highest scorers as well as three of the five leading wicket-takers in the tournament were from Australia.
[src:australia-women-s-national-cricket-team/1978-women-s-cricket-world-cup] Sharon Tredrea featured in both lists, being the second-highest wicket-taker and fourth-highest scorer of the tournament.
[src:australia-women-s-national-cricket-team/1978-women-s-cricket-world-cup] It was originally proposed that South Africa host the World Cup, but this was abandoned to conform with the Apartheid-era sporting boycott of the country.
[src:australia-women-s-national-cricket-team/1978-women-s-cricket-world-cup] The Women's Cricket Association of India (WCAI) then made a successful bid, and served as the primary organiser, with the International Women's Cricket Council (IWCC) providing only limited oversight.
[src:australia-women-s-national-cricket-team/1978-women-s-cricket-world-cup] Along with India, which was making its debut, five other teams were originally invited – Australia, England, the Netherlands, New Zealand, and the West Indies.
[src:australia-women-s-national-cricket-team/1978-women-s-cricket-world-cup] The Netherlands and the West Indies, which had both not previously participated, were forced to withdraw due to financial issues.
[src:australia-women-s-national-cricket-team/1978-women-s-cricket-world-cup] Information is only available for players who played at least one match at the tournament.
[src:australia-women-s-national-cricket-team/1978-women-s-cricket-world-cup] At least five warm-up matches were played against various local Indian teams, all but one of which came before the tournament.
[src:australia-women-s-national-cricket-team/1978-women-s-cricket-world-cup] Both Australia and England went into the last match of the tournament undefeated, which meant it functioned as a *de facto* final, akin to the Uruguay v Brazil match at the 1950 Football World Cup.
[src:australia-women-s-national-cricket-team/1978-women-s-cricket-world-cup] The World Cup was reportedly poorly organised, with the conflicts between the WCAI, Indian state governments and the national governments.
[src:australia-women-s-national-cricket-team/1978-women-s-cricket-world-cup] The visiting international teams were advised that the tournament would be held from 29 December 1977 to 23 January 1978 and were requested to arrive in mid-December for warm-up matches.
[src:australia-women-s-national-cricket-team/1978-women-s-cricket-world-cup] They arrived to find that no matches had been organised; the WCAI issued an itinerary after the first match, but only around half of the anticipated matches were completed.
[src:australia-women-s-national-cricket-team/1978-women-s-cricket-world-cup] The tournament nonetheless attracted large crowds.
[src:australia-women-s-national-cricket-team/1978-women-s-cricket-world-cup] England's Megan Lear later recounted that the "most memorable part of [the] tournament was playing in front of crowds of 40,000 plus".
[src:australia-women-s-national-cricket-team/1978-women-s-cricket-world-cup] The Indians were the first women's team to play in trousers; at the previous World Cup all teams had played in skirts.
[src:australia-women-s-national-cricket-team/1978-women-s-cricket-world-cup] The top five runscorers are included in this table, ranked by runs scored and then by batting average.
[src:australia-women-s-national-cricket-team/1978-women-s-cricket-world-cup] The top five wicket takers are listed in this table, ranked by wickets taken and then by bowling average.
[src:australia-women-s-national-cricket-team/1982-women-s-cricket-world-cup-final] The **1982 Women's Cricket World Cup Final** was a one-day cricket match between the Australia women's national cricket team and the England women's cricket team played on 7 February 1982 at Lancaster Park in Christchurch, New Zealand.
[src:australia-women-s-national-cricket-team/1982-women-s-cricket-world-cup-final] It marked the culmination of the 1982 Women's Cricket World Cup, the third edition of the tournament, but was the first time a final had been held; both the previous events had been round-robin tournaments.
[src:australia-women-s-national-cricket-team/1982-women-s-cricket-world-cup-final] Both Australia and England had previously won the competition; England won the inaugural tournament in 1973, while Australia won in 1978.
[src:australia-women-s-national-cricket-team/1982-women-s-cricket-world-cup-final] Australia won the match by three wickets to claim their second world title.
[src:australia-women-s-national-cricket-team/1982-women-s-cricket-world-cup-final] Australia and England finished first and second in the league-stage to claim their places in the final.
[src:australia-women-s-national-cricket-team/1982-women-s-cricket-world-cup-final] Australia had gone unbeaten throughout the round-robin, having won eleven of their matches and tied with England in the other.
[src:australia-women-s-national-cricket-team/1982-women-s-cricket-world-cup-final] England had won seven of their matches, lost three and tied twice, and finished 14 points behind Australia and 6 ahead of New Zealand.
[src:australia-women-s-national-cricket-team/1982-women-s-cricket-world-cup-final] The final was umpired by Dickie Bird and Fred Goodall.
[src:australia-women-s-national-cricket-team/1982-women-s-cricket-world-cup-final] England batted first in the final, and scored slowly, particularly against Australia's spin bowling.
[src:australia-women-s-national-cricket-team/1982-women-s-cricket-world-cup-final] Jan Southgate top-scored for England with 53 runs, as they made 151 for five.
[src:australia-women-s-national-cricket-team/1982-women-s-cricket-world-cup-final] In response, Australia initially struggled, losing their first three wickets for 28 runs.
[src:australia-women-s-national-cricket-team/1982-women-s-cricket-world-cup-final] A partnership between Karen Read and Sharon Tredrea recovered their innings, before quick scoring from Jen Jacobs and Marie Cornish saw them to victory.
[src:australia-women-s-national-cricket-team/1982-women-s-cricket-world-cup-final] The 1982 Women's Cricket World Cup was the third Women's Cricket World Cup.
[src:australia-women-s-national-cricket-team/1982-women-s-cricket-world-cup-final] The first had been held in 1973, pre-dating the first men's Cricket World Cup by two years.
[src:australia-women-s-national-cricket-team/1982-women-s-cricket-world-cup-final] The 1982 tournament featured five teams; Australia, England, India, New Zealand and an International XI.
[src:australia-women-s-national-cricket-team/1982-women-s-cricket-world-cup-final] It took place between 10 January and 7 February, featuring 31 matches over 29 days.
[src:australia-women-s-national-cricket-team/1982-women-s-cricket-world-cup-final] England had won the first world cup on home soil, before Australia claimed the second, held in India.
[src:australia-women-s-national-cricket-team/1982-women-s-cricket-world-cup-final] Neither tournament had featured a final, but had rather been league competitions, in which the team which finished with the most points won.
[src:australia-women-s-national-cricket-team/1982-women-s-cricket-world-cup-final] Each team played twelve matches during the round-robin stage of the tournament, facing each other three times.
[src:australia-women-s-national-cricket-team/1982-women-s-cricket-world-cup-final] The top two teams would progress directly to the final, the first time the tournament would feature a final.
[src:australia-women-s-national-cricket-team/1982-women-s-cricket-world-cup-final] Australia remained unbeaten; they won eleven of their matches and tied their other, against England.
[src:australia-women-s-national-cricket-team/1982-women-s-cricket-world-cup-final] On the opening day of the tournament, Jill Kennare scored 98 runs, as Australia beat India by 153 runs.
[src:australia-women-s-national-cricket-team/1982-women-s-cricket-world-cup-final] Four days later, England's Jan Brittin made the highest score of the tournament, 138 not out, against the International XI.
[src:australia-women-s-national-cricket-team/1982-women-s-cricket-world-cup-final] England won seven of their matches, lost three times (twice against Australia and once against India), and tied two matches (in addition to the tie against Australia, they also tied with New Zealand).
[src:australia-women-s-national-cricket-team/1982-women-s-cricket-world-cup-final] Australia finished top of the table with 46 points, and England were second with 32.
[src:australia-women-s-national-cricket-team/1982-women-s-cricket-world-cup-final] Hosts New Zealand scored 26 points, India 16, while the International XI lost all their matches to finish with no points.
[src:australia-women-s-national-cricket-team/1982-women-s-cricket-world-cup-final] The final was played at Lancaster Park, in Christchurch, New Zealand, on 7 February, in front of a crowd of around 3,000.
[src:australia-women-s-national-cricket-team/1982-women-s-cricket-world-cup-final] The match was umpired by a New Zealander, Fred Goodall, and the English umpire, Dickie Bird.
[src:australia-women-s-national-cricket-team/1982-women-s-cricket-world-cup-final] By officiating in the match, Bird became the only umpire to stand in both a men's and women's World Cup final, having previously umpired the 1975 Cricket World Cup Final.
[src:australia-women-s-national-cricket-team/1982-women-s-cricket-world-cup-final] The England captain, Susan Goatman, won the toss, and chose to bat first on a pitch described as "placid" by the Australian press.
[src:australia-women-s-national-cricket-team/1982-women-s-cricket-world-cup-final] The England opening batters, Brittin and Goatman, scored slowly, putting on 42 runs together before Brittin was dismissed by a diving catch from Marie Cornish off her own bowling for 17 runs.
[src:australia-women-s-national-cricket-team/1982-women-s-cricket-world-cup-final] England scored another 12 runs before Goatman was bowled by Lyn Fullston for 29.
[src:australia-women-s-national-cricket-team/1982-women-s-cricket-world-cup-final] Fullston was also the bowler for the next wicket; Chris Watmough was caught at mid-on by Kennare for 9, and England were 63 for three.
[src:australia-women-s-national-cricket-team/1982-women-s-cricket-world-cup-final] England's experienced partnership of Jan Southgate and Rachael Heyhoe-Flint aimed to recover the England innings, but were restricted by Australia's spin bowling.
[src:australia-women-s-national-cricket-team/1982-women-s-cricket-world-cup-final] Southgate, who made the team's highest score, 53 runs, was caught by Sharyn Hill off the bowling of Sharon Tredrea, while Heyhoe-Flint was caught by Fullston off Tredrea's bowling for 29.
[src:australia-women-s-national-cricket-team/1982-women-s-cricket-world-cup-final] Australia's reply started poorly; they lost three wickets in the first eleven overs, taking the score to 28 for three.
[src:australia-women-s-national-cricket-team/1982-women-s-cricket-world-cup-final] Their opening pair, Peta Verco and Hill, were both caught by Goatman off the bowling of Avril Starling, while Kennare was the first of three Australian to be run out.
[src:australia-women-s-national-cricket-team/1982-women-s-cricket-world-cup-final] Karen Read and Australia's captain, Tredrea, formed a solid partnership and steadied their team's innings.
[src:australia-women-s-national-cricket-team/1982-women-s-cricket-world-cup-final] The pair scored 54 runs together before they were both dismissed in quick succession; Read was caught by Southgate off the bowling of Janet Tedstone for 32, while Tredrea was caught behind off Carole Hodges for 25.
[src:australia-women-s-national-cricket-team/1982-women-s-cricket-world-cup-final] Australia were 97 for five, needing another 55 runs to win.
[src:australia-women-s-national-cricket-team/1982-women-s-cricket-world-cup-final] England adopted a tight field to minimise Australia's scoring options, but Jen Jacobs lofted the ball over the fielders during her innings of 37, which *The Times* described as one of the highlights of the match.
[src:australia-women-s-national-cricket-team/1982-women-s-cricket-world-cup-final] Cornish, who had been playing a support role until that point, then assumed control and scored seven runs from one over bowled by Enid Bakewell, but with Australia still needing seven runs, Raelee Thompson was run out.
[src:australia-women-s-national-cricket-team/1982-women-s-cricket-world-cup-final] *The Times* praised England's "excellent work in the field", though it was ultimately a mis-field that gave Australia their winning run in the penultimate over.
[src:australia-women-s-national-cricket-team/1982-women-s-cricket-world-cup-final] Cornish remained not out with 24 runs, and Australia won the match by three wickets with six balls remaining.
[src:australia-women-s-national-cricket-team/1982-women-s-cricket-world-cup-final] England's Brittin finished at the tournament's leading run-scorer, with 391 runs, while Australia's Fullston took the most wickets, with 23.
[src:australia-women-s-national-cricket-team/1982-women-s-cricket-world-cup-final] England's captain, Goatman, announced her retirement after the tournament; she had led England for three years, having previously captained the Young England team during the 1973 tournament.
[src:australia-women-s-national-cricket-team/1982-women-s-cricket-world-cup-final] Southgate was appointed as her replacement as captain.
[src:australia-women-s-national-cricket-team/1982-women-s-cricket-world-cup-final] Writing for *Wisden*, Netta Rheinberg noted that England could no longer "consider themselves able to fend off all challenges", and that as a result they implemented efforts to improve cricket at a junior level, to encourage future talent.
[src:australia-women-s-national-cricket-team/1982-women-s-cricket-world-cup-final] Australia and England met again in the final of the 1988 Women's Cricket World Cup, when Australia won by eight wickets.
[src:australia-women-s-national-cricket-team/1982-women-s-cricket-world-cup-final] Between them, Australia and England have won ten of the eleven Women's Cricket World Cups; only in 2000 did one of the pair fail to win, when New Zealand beat Australia in the final.
[src:australia-women-s-national-cricket-team/1982-women-s-cricket-world-cup] The **1982 Women's Cricket World Cup**, known as the **1982 Hansells Vita Fresh World Cup** for sponsorship purposes, was an international cricket tournament played in New Zealand from 10 January to 7 February 1982.
[src:australia-women-s-national-cricket-team/1982-women-s-cricket-world-cup] Hosted by New Zealand for the first time, it was the third edition of the Women's Cricket World Cup, coming four years after the previous 1978 World Cup in India.
[src:australia-women-s-national-cricket-team/1982-women-s-cricket-world-cup] The tournament, which featured a triple round-robin, was at the time the longest World Cup both in duration and the number of matches played.
[src:australia-women-s-national-cricket-team/1982-women-s-cricket-world-cup] Five teams were originally invited in addition to the hosts, but the Netherlands were unable to attend and the West Indies withdrew in protest at New Zealand hosting the 1981 South Africa rugby union tour during the apartheid-era in South Africa.
[src:australia-women-s-national-cricket-team/1982-women-s-cricket-world-cup] Those teams were instead replaced by a composite International XI team.
[src:australia-women-s-national-cricket-team/1982-women-s-cricket-world-cup] Australia did not lose a single match, winning its second consecutive tournament by defeating England in the final at Lancaster Park, Christchurch.
[src:australia-women-s-national-cricket-team/1982-women-s-cricket-world-cup] Australia's thirteen matches without defeat were part of a greater 24-match unbeaten run, extending from 1978 to 1985, which was a One Day International (ODI) record, before Australia itself broke it in 2021, with an unbeaten streak of 26 matches extending from 2018 to 2021.
[src:australia-women-s-national-cricket-team/1982-women-s-cricket-world-cup] The World Cup was marked by its low scoring, with only one team recording more than 250 runs in an innings, and was also notable for featuring two matches that were tied – the first between England and New Zealand, and the second between England and Australia.
[src:australia-women-s-national-cricket-team/1982-women-s-cricket-world-cup] They were the first ties in international women's cricket.
[src:australia-women-s-national-cricket-team/1982-women-s-cricket-world-cup] England's Jan Brittin led the tournament in runs, while Australian spinner Lyn Fullston led the tournament in wickets.
[src:australia-women-s-national-cricket-team/1982-women-s-cricket-world-cup] Jack Hayward and Rachael Heyhoe-Flint organised the 1973 Women's Cricket World Cup, predating the first men's Cricket World Cup by two years.
[src:australia-women-s-national-cricket-team/1982-women-s-cricket-world-cup] The tournament was played as a league format; the team who topped the points table at the conclusion would be champions.
[src:australia-women-s-national-cricket-team/1982-women-s-cricket-world-cup] England beat Australia in the last match of the tournament to become the first Women's World Cup winners.
[src:australia-women-s-national-cricket-team/1982-women-s-cricket-world-cup] The second Women's Cricket World Cup was scheduled to take place in South Africa in 1978, but with that country facing increasing sporting boycotts due to its apartheid policies, and withdrawals for financial reasons by the Netherlands and West Indies, the tournament was in jeopardy.
[src:australia-women-s-national-cricket-team/1982-women-s-cricket-world-cup] The 1978 Women's Cricket World Cup was belatedly relocated to India, and featured only four teams.
[src:australia-women-s-national-cricket-team/1982-women-s-cricket-world-cup] The tournament was once again played in a league format, but as in 1973, the final group match acted as a de facto final: Australia beat England to become champions.
[src:australia-women-s-national-cricket-team/1982-women-s-cricket-world-cup] During the 1978 World Cup, the International Women's Cricket Council (IWCC) met.
[src:australia-women-s-national-cricket-team/1982-women-s-cricket-world-cup] The IWCC had not been involved in the running of either of the first two world cups, but felt that there had been a lack of organisation, and announced that they would be more involved with future world cups.
[src:australia-women-s-national-cricket-team/1982-women-s-cricket-world-cup] Despite the involvement of the IWCC, the organisation of the 1982 event still primarily rested on the New Zealand Women's Cricket Council; which itself was mostly formed of the players themselves.
[src:australia-women-s-national-cricket-team/1982-women-s-cricket-world-cup] They spent eighteen months planning the tournament.
[src:australia-women-s-national-cricket-team/1982-women-s-cricket-world-cup] Their efforts resulted in the Women's World Cup having a title sponsor for the first time; it was officially known as the Hansells Vita Fresh World Cup.
[src:australia-women-s-national-cricket-team/1982-women-s-cricket-world-cup] Unlike the two previous women's world cups, the 1982 tournament featured a final.
[src:australia-women-s-national-cricket-team/1982-women-s-cricket-world-cup] A round-robin league stage involved each of the five teams playing each other three times each; a total of 30 group matches, from which the top two teams qualified for the final.
[src:australia-women-s-national-cricket-team/1982-women-s-cricket-world-cup] The tournament took place over 29 days, from 10 January to 7 February.
[src:australia-women-s-national-cricket-team/1982-women-s-cricket-world-cup] Each match was played as a 60-overs-per-side contest.
[src:australia-women-s-national-cricket-team/1982-women-s-cricket-world-cup] Five teams were invited: Australia, England, India, the Netherlands and the West Indies, but as in 1978, South Africa were not invited due to the ongoing boycott.
[src:australia-women-s-national-cricket-team/1982-women-s-cricket-world-cup] Despite the increased sponsorship, and the involvement of the IWCC, participating teams and players had to fund their own visit.
[src:australia-women-s-national-cricket-team/1982-women-s-cricket-world-cup] For example, each Indian player had to pay ₨10,000 (roughly £570, or US$1,000 at the time).
[src:australia-women-s-national-cricket-team/1982-women-s-cricket-world-cup] This cost was prohibitive for the Dutch team, who withdrew from the tournament, as they had four years earlier.
[src:australia-women-s-national-cricket-team/1982-women-s-cricket-world-cup] The West Indies also pulled out, in protest that New Zealand had hosted the apartheid-era South African rugby team in 1981.
[src:australia-women-s-national-cricket-team/1982-women-s-cricket-world-cup] In order to prevent another four-team competition, the organising committee decided to invite a selection of players to form an International XI, as had featured at the 1973 World Cup.
[src:australia-women-s-national-cricket-team/1982-women-s-cricket-world-cup] The tournament began on 10 January 1982 with two matches played in Auckland.
[src:australia-women-s-national-cricket-team/1982-women-s-cricket-world-cup] Australia beat India by 153 runs, a new record margin in women's ODIs.
[src:australia-women-s-national-cricket-team/1982-women-s-cricket-world-cup] In the other match, another record was set; England and New Zealand played out the first tied match in women's ODIs.
[src:australia-women-s-national-cricket-team/1982-women-s-cricket-world-cup] The tournament remained in Auckland for the next round of matches on 12 January; England beat India by four wickets, while New Zealand surpassed the record set by Australia two days earlier, by beating the International XI by 184 runs, a record which would stand for six years.
[src:australia-women-s-national-cricket-team/1982-women-s-cricket-world-cup] New Zealand set another new record in their next match two days later, when they bowled India out for what was, at the time, the lowest total in women's ODIs: 37.
[src:australia-women-s-national-cricket-team/1982-women-s-cricket-world-cup] On the same day in Hamilton, England beat the International XI by 132 runs.
[src:australia-women-s-national-cricket-team/1982-women-s-cricket-world-cup] Australia beat New Zealand by eight wickets and England by 44 runs on consecutive days in New Plymouth, while India completed a 79-run victory over the International XI in Napier.
[src:australia-women-s-national-cricket-team/1982-women-s-cricket-world-cup] England remained in New Plymouth, and beat New Zealand by seven wickets the day after their loss to Australia.
[src:australia-women-s-national-cricket-team/1982-women-s-cricket-world-cup] Continuing to move south, Australia beat the International XI by 64 runs in Palmerston North, while on the same day India beat England by 47 runs, India's first win over England, and a victory *The Guardian* described at the time as India's "best ever result in the World Cup".
[src:australia-women-s-national-cricket-team/1982-women-s-cricket-world-cup] On 21 January, New Zealand beat the International XI by 97 runs.
[src:australia-women-s-national-cricket-team/1982-women-s-cricket-world-cup] Two days later, Australia beat England by six wickets.
[src:australia-women-s-national-cricket-team/1982-women-s-cricket-world-cup] England played again the next day, beating the International XI by nine wickets, while New Zealand beat India by eight wickets.
[src:australia-women-s-national-cricket-team/1982-women-s-cricket-world-cup] Australia then won twice in two days, beating the International XI by 146 runs and India by four wickets.
[src:australia-women-s-national-cricket-team/1982-women-s-cricket-world-cup] In the last round of matches played in the North Island, England beat New Zealand by five wickets, New Zealand then lost to Australia by 69 runs, before India beat the International XI by 78 runs.
[src:australia-women-s-national-cricket-team/1982-women-s-cricket-world-cup] The tournament moved to the South Island on 30 January; Australia beat the International XI by 76 runs in Dunedin.
[src:australia-women-s-national-cricket-team/1982-women-s-cricket-world-cup] The next day, England beat India by ten wickets, and New Zealand beat the International XI by 84 runs.
[src:australia-women-s-national-cricket-team/1982-women-s-cricket-world-cup] Australia and England tied the 25th match of the tournament; it was England's second tie of the group stage, and the second ever in women's ODIs.
[src:australia-women-s-national-cricket-team/1982-women-s-cricket-world-cup] India were once again bowled out cheaply by New Zealand in their next match, and were beaten by eight wickets.
[src:australia-women-s-national-cricket-team/1982-women-s-cricket-world-cup] On 4 February, Australia and England both posted large totals in their victories; Australia scored 193 for five as they beat India by 39 runs, while England scored 242 for four in a 113-run over the International XI.
[src:australia-women-s-national-cricket-team/1982-women-s-cricket-world-cup] Two days later, Australia beat New Zealand by 41 runs, and India beat the International XI by 14 runs; meaning that the International XI did not record a win in the competition.
[src:australia-women-s-national-cricket-team/1982-women-s-cricket-world-cup] In the final match of the group stage, Australia beat England by three wickets.
[src:australia-women-s-national-cricket-team/1982-women-s-cricket-world-cup] Having remained unbeaten throughout the tournament, only dropping points in their tie with England, Australia finished top of the table.
[src:australia-women-s-national-cricket-team/1982-women-s-cricket-world-cup] England trailed them by fourteen points in second place; both qualified for the final.
[src:australia-women-s-national-cricket-team/1982-women-s-cricket-world-cup] New Zealand won all their matches against India and the International XI, but against Australia and England, only gained points during their tie with England.
[src:australia-women-s-national-cricket-team/1982-women-s-cricket-world-cup] India's victory over England was their only win that did not come against the International XI.
[src:australia-women-s-national-cricket-team/1982-women-s-cricket-world-cup] The final was the only match of the tournament played at Lancaster Park, Christchurch, and took place in front of a crowd of 3,000.
[src:australia-women-s-national-cricket-team/1982-women-s-cricket-world-cup] Dickie Bird became the only umpire to stand in both a men's and women's World Cup final.
[src:australia-women-s-national-cricket-team/1982-women-s-cricket-world-cup] They scored slowly until the last ten overs of their innings; Jan Southgate made their highest score, with 53 runs, but found batting difficulty against Australia's spin bowling.
[src:australia-women-s-national-cricket-team/1982-women-s-cricket-world-cup] In the last ten overs, England played more expansively, and eventually finished with 151 runs, meaning that Australia would need to score 152 to win.
[src:australia-women-s-national-cricket-team/1982-women-s-cricket-world-cup] Australia lost three wickets early in their chase, but were steadied by a partnership between Karen Read and Sharon Tredrea.
[src:australia-women-s-national-cricket-team/1982-women-s-cricket-world-cup] Quick scoring from Jen Jacobs and Marie Cornish late-on in the innings helped Australia to their target with six balls remaining, securing a three-wicket victory, and their second World Cup title.
[src:australia-women-s-national-cricket-team/1982-women-s-cricket-world-cup] England's Jan Brittin finished with the most runs during the World Cup, having accumulated 391, ahead of the 383 scored by Lynne Thomas of the International XI and Susan Goatman, also of England, who scored 374.
[src:australia-women-s-national-cricket-team/1982-women-s-cricket-world-cup] Brittin also made the highest score of the tournament, when she scored 138 not out against the International XI.
[src:australia-women-s-national-cricket-team/1982-women-s-cricket-world-cup] The only other century of the tournament came against the same opposition: Barbara Bevege's 101.
[src:australia-women-s-national-cricket-team/1982-women-s-cricket-world-cup] The best averages of the competition were achieved by England's Heyhoe-Flint, with 47.83, and two Australians, Jill Kennare (43.87) and Lyn Fullston (41.00).
[src:australia-women-s-national-cricket-team/1982-women-s-cricket-world-cup] Amongst the bowlers, Fullston took the most wickets (23), followed by Jackie Lord of New Zealand, with 22, and India's Shubhangi Kulkarni, who took 20.
[src:australia-women-s-national-cricket-team/1982-women-s-cricket-world-cup] Lord had the best bowling figures in an innings, when she took six wickets against India.
[src:australia-women-s-national-cricket-team/1982-women-s-cricket-world-cup] The only other bowler to take five wickets in an innings was Fullston, who did so against New Zealand, taking five for 27.
[src:australia-women-s-national-cricket-team/1982-women-s-cricket-world-cup] Kulkarni had the best bowling average in the World Cup, collecting her wickets at 11.70.
[src:australia-women-s-national-cricket-team/1982-women-s-cricket-world-cup] She was followed by Fullston (12.00) and Lord (12.40).
[src:australia-women-s-national-cricket-team/1982-women-s-cricket-world-cup] The most economical bowler was New Zealand's Sue Brown, who conceded 1.53 runs per over, followed by a pair of Australians; Cornish (1.76) and Denise Martin (1.77).
[src:australia-women-s-national-cricket-team/1988-women-s-cricket-world-cup-final] The **1988 Women's Cricket World Cup Final** was a one-day cricket match between Australia and England played on 18 December 1988 at the Melbourne Cricket Ground in Melbourne, Australia.
[src:australia-women-s-national-cricket-team/1988-women-s-cricket-world-cup-final] It marked the culmination of the 1988 Women's Cricket World Cup, the fourth edition of the tournament.
[src:australia-women-s-national-cricket-team/1988-women-s-cricket-world-cup-final] Both Australia and England had previously won the competition; England won the inaugural tournament in 1973, while Australia won in both 1978 and 1982.
[src:australia-women-s-national-cricket-team/1988-women-s-cricket-world-cup-final] Australia won the match by eight wickets to claim their third world title.
[src:australia-women-s-national-cricket-team/1988-women-s-cricket-world-cup-final] England batted first in the final, but were hindered by a slow outfield, and found scoring difficult.
[src:australia-women-s-national-cricket-team/1988-women-s-cricket-world-cup-final] The humid conditions helped Australia's spin bowlers, Lyn Fullston and Lyn Larsen, who combined for five wickets.
[src:australia-women-s-national-cricket-team/1988-women-s-cricket-world-cup-final] Jan Brittin top-scored for England with 46 runs, as they made 127 for seven.
[src:australia-women-s-national-cricket-team/1988-women-s-cricket-world-cup-final] In response, Australia initially struggled, losing two early wickets for 14 runs.
[src:australia-women-s-national-cricket-team/1988-women-s-cricket-world-cup-final] An unbroken partnership of 115 runs between Lindsay Reeler and Denise Annetts saw Australia to victory with more than 15 overs remaining.
[src:australia-women-s-national-cricket-team/1988-women-s-cricket-world-cup-final] The 1988 Women's Cricket World Cup was the fourth Women's Cricket World Cup.
[src:australia-women-s-national-cricket-team/1988-women-s-cricket-world-cup-final] The 1988 tournament featured five teams; Australia, England, Ireland, the Netherlands and New Zealand.
[src:australia-women-s-national-cricket-team/1988-women-s-cricket-world-cup-final] It took place between 29 November and 18 December 1988, featuring 22 matches over 20 days.
[src:australia-women-s-national-cricket-team/1988-women-s-cricket-world-cup-final] England had won the first World Cup on home soil, before Australia claimed both the next two.
[src:australia-women-s-national-cricket-team/1988-women-s-cricket-world-cup-final] Neither of the first two tournaments had featured a final, but had rather been league competitions, in which the team which finished with the most points won.
[src:australia-women-s-national-cricket-team/1988-women-s-cricket-world-cup-final] Australia had defeated England by three wickets in the final of the 1982 World Cup.
[src:australia-women-s-national-cricket-team/1988-women-s-cricket-world-cup-final] Each team played eight matches during the round-robin stage of the tournament, facing each other twice.
[src:australia-women-s-national-cricket-team/1988-women-s-cricket-world-cup-final] The top two teams would progress directly to the final.
[src:australia-women-s-national-cricket-team/1988-women-s-cricket-world-cup-final] Australia won all but one of their matches.
[src:australia-women-s-national-cricket-team/1988-women-s-cricket-world-cup-final] Their 255-run win over the Netherlands on the opening day of the tournament remained the largest win by runs until 1997.
[src:australia-women-s-national-cricket-team/1988-women-s-cricket-world-cup-final] Australia's only loss came against England, who beat them by 15 runs.
[src:australia-women-s-national-cricket-team/1988-women-s-cricket-world-cup-final] Australia's opening batters, Lindsay Reeler and Ruth Buckstein, scored four of the five centuries made during the tournament; Reeler's 108 not out against New Zealand was the only one that was not scored against the Netherlands.
[src:australia-women-s-national-cricket-team/1988-women-s-cricket-world-cup-final] England won six of their matches, and lost two; against Australia and New Zealand.
[src:australia-women-s-national-cricket-team/1988-women-s-cricket-world-cup-final] Australia finished top of the group with 28 points, followed by England whose 24 points were four more than New Zealand in third.
[src:australia-women-s-national-cricket-team/1988-women-s-cricket-world-cup-final] Ireland and the Netherlands were well behind, with 8 and 0 points respectively.
[src:australia-women-s-national-cricket-team/1988-women-s-cricket-world-cup-final] The final was held at the Melbourne Cricket Ground, in Melbourne, Australia, on 18 December 1988.
[src:australia-women-s-national-cricket-team/1988-women-s-cricket-world-cup-final] The match was broadcast live on radio and on ABC Television in Australia, and in front of a crowd of 3,326.
[src:australia-women-s-national-cricket-team/1988-women-s-cricket-world-cup-final] The England captain, Jane Powell, won the toss and decided to bat first.
[src:australia-women-s-national-cricket-team/1988-women-s-cricket-world-cup-final] Her decision was primarily based on Australia's public aversion to batting second, and having to chase a target.
[src:australia-women-s-national-cricket-team/1988-women-s-cricket-world-cup-final] Heather Smith of *The Sydney Morning Herald* suggested that, due to the wet conditions, "England may have unwittingly helped their own downfall".
[src:australia-women-s-national-cricket-team/1988-women-s-cricket-world-cup-final] Carole Hodges and Wendy Watson opened the batting for England, and neither scored a run until the sixth over; the only runs attributed to England before that were wides bowled by the Australians, which *The Age* attributed to the "excitement of playing on the MCG for the first time".
[src:australia-women-s-national-cricket-team/1988-women-s-cricket-world-cup-final] After 25 overs, England had scored 40 runs without losing a wicket, but both openers were frustrated by the slow run-rate.
[src:australia-women-s-national-cricket-team/1988-women-s-cricket-world-cup-final] Watson was dismissed two overs later for 17; playing an aggressive shot, she was caught by Denise Annetts at cover off the bowling of Lyn Fullston.
[src:australia-women-s-national-cricket-team/1988-women-s-cricket-world-cup-final] She had shared a 42-run opening partnership with Hodges, but John Woodcock of *The Times* complained that they "lacked pace between the wickets, when something very spritely was needed".
[src:australia-women-s-national-cricket-team/1988-women-s-cricket-world-cup-final] England added ten more runs before Hodges was bowled by a delivery from Lyn Larsen which dislodged her off-bail.
[src:australia-women-s-national-cricket-team/1988-women-s-cricket-world-cup-final] Hodges had scored 23, and England were 52 for two.
[src:australia-women-s-national-cricket-team/1988-women-s-cricket-world-cup-final] Three of England's middle-order batters were dismissed for low scores: their captain, Powell, was caught behind off Larsen's bowling for one run; Karen Hicken was bowled by Fullston for five; Janet Aspinall was caught and bowled by Fullston for two.
[src:australia-women-s-national-cricket-team/1988-women-s-cricket-world-cup-final] Brittin, who had come to the crease when Watson was out, remained not out; England were 74 for five.
[src:australia-women-s-national-cricket-team/1988-women-s-cricket-world-cup-final] After lunch, Brittin and Jo Chamberlain scored more quickly for England, earning praise from both *The Sydney Morning Herald* and *The Times*, but after putting on 26 runs together, Chamberlain was run out for 14 after the ball deflected off the bowler.
[src:australia-women-s-national-cricket-team/1988-women-s-cricket-world-cup-final] Woodcock suggested that Brittin was England's only remaining hope.
[src:australia-women-s-national-cricket-team/1988-women-s-cricket-world-cup-final] Patsy Lovell was trapped leg before wicket for four runs, while Suzie Kitson remained one not out at the end of the innings.
[src:australia-women-s-national-cricket-team/1988-women-s-cricket-world-cup-final] Brittin had made England's highest score, 46 not out.
[src:australia-women-s-national-cricket-team/1988-women-s-cricket-world-cup-final] Woodcock said that: "It was a pity, really, that Brittin had not got in before the 27th over, with the touch she has." England scored 127 runs, a total *The Sydney Morning Herald* said "was never going to be enough".
[src:australia-women-s-national-cricket-team/1988-women-s-cricket-world-cup-final] Throughout their 60-over innings, England scored two boundaries.
[src:australia-women-s-national-cricket-team/1988-women-s-cricket-world-cup-final] In humid conditions, they especially struggled against spin bowling; Fullston took three wickets and allowed 29 runs, while Larsen took two wickets for 22.
[src:australia-women-s-national-cricket-team/1988-women-s-cricket-world-cup-final] The wet outfield also slowed scoring; this dried as the match went on, giving Australia the better of the batting conditions.
[src:australia-women-s-national-cricket-team/1988-women-s-cricket-world-cup-final] In the *Wisden Cricketers' Almanack*, Carol Salmon estimated that the slow outfield cost England between 20 and 30 runs.
[src:australia-women-s-national-cricket-team/1988-women-s-cricket-world-cup-final] Aspinall, who opened the bowling for England, struggled for accuracy; conceding extras, particularly wides, had been a problem for England all tournament and the final was no exception.
[src:australia-women-s-national-cricket-team/1988-women-s-cricket-world-cup-final] In spite of this, England made an early breakthrough: Chamberlain, who according to *The Age* "worried the Australians with her accurate medium-pacers", trapped the Australian opener Buckstein leg before wicket without scoring in the second over.
[src:australia-women-s-national-cricket-team/1988-women-s-cricket-world-cup-final] Australia's next batter, Sharlene Heywood only scored five runs in nine minutes until confusion between herself and Reeler led to Heywood being run out, leaving Australia on 14 for two.
[src:australia-women-s-national-cricket-team/1988-women-s-cricket-world-cup-final] Annetts joined Reeler at the crease, and early in her innings was criticised by *The Age* for "[dangling] a dangerously limp bat".
[src:australia-women-s-national-cricket-team/1988-women-s-cricket-world-cup-final] Reeler was troubled by the quicker bowling of Kitson, and in the 14th over, England were convinced that they had dismissed her, caught behind, but the umpire turned down the appeal.
[src:australia-women-s-national-cricket-team/1988-women-s-cricket-world-cup-final] Reeler claimed the ball had clipped her pads, rather than her bat, before being caught by the wicket-keeper.
[src:australia-women-s-national-cricket-team/1988-women-s-cricket-world-cup-final] After the appeal, Reeler played more circumspectly for a while, before taking the offensive with "elegant driving and delicate cutting", according to *The Age*.
[src:australia-women-s-national-cricket-team/1988-women-s-cricket-world-cup-final] In contrast to Reeler's technical style, Annetts played powerful shots, predominantly into the leg side.
[src:australia-women-s-national-cricket-team/1988-women-s-cricket-world-cup-final] Reeler brought up her 50 and Australia's 100 from successive deliveries; the first a cover drive which went for a boundary, and the second an on drive.
[src:australia-women-s-national-cricket-team/1988-women-s-cricket-world-cup-final] Annetts secured victory with a pull through the on side.
[src:australia-women-s-national-cricket-team/1988-women-s-cricket-world-cup-final] Reeler finished with 59 runs, and Annetts with 48.
[src:australia-women-s-national-cricket-team/1988-women-s-cricket-world-cup-final] The pair shared an unbroken 115-run partnership, and secured victory for Australia with eight wickets and more than 15 overs remaining.
[src:australia-women-s-national-cricket-team/1988-women-s-cricket-world-cup-final] Reeler finished the tournament as the leading run-scorer, with 448 runs, while for the second successive World Cup, Fullston took the most wickets, with 16.
[src:australia-women-s-national-cricket-team/1988-women-s-cricket-world-cup-final] After the tournament, Sharon Tredrea, Australia's vice-captain and former captain, announced her retirement.
[src:australia-women-s-national-cricket-team/1988-women-s-cricket-world-cup-final] She was the only player who had appeared in all four World Cups.
[src:australia-women-s-national-cricket-team/1988-women-s-cricket-world-cup] The **1988 Women's Cricket World Cup**, also known as **1988 Shell Bicentennial Women's World Cup**, was an international cricket tournament played in Australia from 29 November to 18 December 1988.
[src:australia-women-s-national-cricket-team/1988-women-s-cricket-world-cup] Hosted by Australia for the first time, as part of the Bicentenary celebrations, it was the fourth edition of the Women's Cricket World Cup, and came six years after the preceding 1982 World Cup in New Zealand.
[src:australia-women-s-national-cricket-team/1988-women-s-cricket-world-cup] The tournament was organised by the International Women's Cricket Council (IWCC), with matches played over 60 overs.
[src:australia-women-s-national-cricket-team/1988-women-s-cricket-world-cup] Australia won the tournament for a third consecutive time, defeating England in the final by eight wickets.
[src:australia-women-s-national-cricket-team/1988-women-s-cricket-world-cup] New Zealand defeated Ireland in the third-place playoff, while the Netherlands, the only other team at the tournament, placed fifth and last after failing to win a single match.
[src:australia-women-s-national-cricket-team/1988-women-s-cricket-world-cup] Both Ireland and the Netherlands were making their tournament debuts.
[src:australia-women-s-national-cricket-team/1988-women-s-cricket-world-cup] India had been invited to compete, as they had at the previous two tournaments, but were forced to withdraw after failing to secure enough money from sponsors.
[src:australia-women-s-national-cricket-team/1988-women-s-cricket-world-cup] Two Australians, Lindsay Reeler and Lyn Fullston, led the tournament in runs and wickets, respectively.
[src:australia-women-s-national-cricket-team/1988-women-s-cricket-world-cup] The player of the series was English all-rounder Carole Hodges, who placed third for runs scored and second for wickets taken.
[src:australia-women-s-national-cricket-team/1988-women-s-cricket-world-cup] She received a Waterford Crystal trophy valued at A$4,000, donated by an Irish firm, R&A Bailey.
[src:australia-women-s-national-cricket-team/1988-women-s-cricket-world-cup] At least five warm-up matches were played against Australian state and invitational teams, which were interspersed throughout the tournament.
[src:australia-women-s-national-cricket-team/1988-women-s-cricket-world-cup] The final, held at the Melbourne Cricket Ground, was broadcast live on radio and on ABC Television.
[src:australia-women-s-national-cricket-team/1988-women-s-cricket-world-cup] It was attended by around 3,000 people, although the ground had a capacity at the time of over 90,000.
[src:australia-women-s-national-cricket-team/1988-women-s-cricket-world-cup] Janette Brittin, who played for England in the match, later described the venue as having "wall-to-wall seating with no one sitting in them", making it "a very large and a very lonely place".
[src:australia-women-s-national-cricket-team/1988-women-s-cricket-world-cup] No women's cricket had been played there since 1949.
[src:australia-women-s-national-cricket-team/1993-women-s-cricket-world-cup] The **1993 Women's Cricket World Cup** was an international cricket tournament played in England from 20 July to 1 August 1993.
[src:australia-women-s-national-cricket-team/1993-women-s-cricket-world-cup] Hosted by England for the second time, it was the fifth edition of the Women's Cricket World Cup, and came over four years after the preceding 1988 World Cup in Australia.
[src:australia-women-s-national-cricket-team/1993-women-s-cricket-world-cup] It was a tournament "run on a shoestring", and was close to being cancelled until a £90,000 donation was received from the Foundation for Sport and the Arts.
[src:australia-women-s-national-cricket-team/1993-women-s-cricket-world-cup] England won the tournament for a second time, defeating New Zealand in the final by 67 runs.
[src:australia-women-s-national-cricket-team/1993-women-s-cricket-world-cup] A record eight teams participated, with Denmark, India, and the West Indies joining the five teams from the 1988 edition.
[src:australia-women-s-national-cricket-team/1993-women-s-cricket-world-cup] Denmark and the West Indies were making their tournament debuts.
[src:australia-women-s-national-cricket-team/1993-women-s-cricket-world-cup] England's Jan Brittin was the tournament's highest run-scorer, while her captain Karen Smithies and New Zealand's Julie Harris led the tournament in wickets.
[src:australia-women-s-national-cricket-team/1993-women-s-cricket-world-cup] Eleven warm-up matches were played against various English teams, all before the beginning of the tournament.
[src:australia-women-s-national-cricket-team/1993-women-s-cricket-world-cup] The final at Lord's was attended by 4,500 spectators, including the prime minister of the United Kingdom, John Major.
[src:australia-women-s-national-cricket-team/1993-women-s-cricket-world-cup] The match was broadcast live on BBC's *Grandstand*, and England's victory received front-page and back-page coverage in all of the major national newspapers, a first for women's cricket.
[src:australia-women-s-national-cricket-team/1993-women-s-cricket-world-cup] England's performance was often contrasted with that of the English men's team, which had lost the 1993 Ashes series to Australia less than a week earlier.
[src:australia-women-s-national-cricket-team/1993-women-s-cricket-world-cup] The Women's Cricket Association (WCA) was praised for its management of the final, but the increased media coverage also led to some criticism of its role in the sport as a whole.
[src:australia-women-s-national-cricket-team/1993-women-s-cricket-world-cup] The top five runscorers are included in this table, ranked by runs scored, then by batting average, then alphabetically by surname.
[src:australia-women-s-national-cricket-team/australia-women-s-national-cricket-team-p01] The **Australian women's national cricket team**, formerly known as the **Southern Stars**, represent Australia in international cricket.
[src:australia-women-s-national-cricket-team/australia-women-s-national-cricket-team-p01] Currently captained by Sophie Molineux and coached by Shelley Nitschke, they are the top team in all world rankings assigned by the International Cricket Council.
[src:australia-women-s-national-cricket-team/australia-women-s-national-cricket-team-p01] Australia played their first Test match in 1934–35 against England.
[src:australia-women-s-national-cricket-team/australia-women-s-national-cricket-team-p01] The two teams now compete biennially for the Women's Ashes.
[src:australia-women-s-national-cricket-team/australia-women-s-national-cricket-team-p01] A rich history with New Zealand stretches back almost as far while strong rivalries have also developed more recently with India and the West Indies, manifesting predominantly via limited overs cricket.
[src:australia-women-s-national-cricket-team/australia-women-s-national-cricket-team-p01] In the 50-over format of the game, Australia have won more World Cups than all other teams combined—capturing the 1978, 1982, 1988, 1997, 2005, 2013 and 2022 titles.
[src:australia-women-s-national-cricket-team/australia-women-s-national-cricket-team-p01] They have achieved similarly emphatic success in Twenty20 cricket by winning the ICC Women's T20 World Cup in 2010, 2012, 2014, 2018, 2020, 2023 and 2026.
[src:australia-women-s-national-cricket-team/australia-women-s-national-cricket-team-p01] In 2003, Women's Cricket Australia (WCA) and the Australian Cricket Board (ACB) merged to form a single governing body, known as Cricket Australia (CA), which remains to this day.
[src:australia-women-s-national-cricket-team/australia-women-s-national-cricket-team-p01] A survey conducted by TrueNorth Research in April 2020 showed the national women's cricket team have the strongest emotional connection with Australian sports fans.
[src:australia-women-s-national-cricket-team/australia-women-s-national-cricket-team-p01] Organised cricket has been played by women in Australia since no later than 1874 when the first recorded match took place in Bendigo.
[src:australia-women-s-national-cricket-team/australia-women-s-national-cricket-team-p01] Competitions have existed at state level since the early-1900s and at national level since 1931–32.
[src:australia-women-s-national-cricket-team/australia-women-s-national-cricket-team-p01] The Australian Women's Cricket Council (AWCC) was formed in March 1931 to administer and develop the game at the national level.
[src:australia-women-s-national-cricket-team/australia-women-s-national-cricket-team-p01] The original members of the AWCC were Victoria, New South Wales and Queensland.
[src:australia-women-s-national-cricket-team/australia-women-s-national-cricket-team-p01] South Australia and Western Australia joined in 1934, while ACT and Tasmania affiliated in 1977 and 1982 respectively.
[src:australia-women-s-national-cricket-team/australia-women-s-national-cricket-team-p01] England became the first international women's cricket team to visit Australia, touring in the summer of 1934–35 to compete in a series against an Australian team captained by Margaret Peden.
[src:australia-women-s-national-cricket-team/australia-women-s-national-cricket-team-p01] Three Test matches—the first-ever involving women—were played during the series which received significant public and media interest.
[src:australia-women-s-national-cricket-team/australia-women-s-national-cricket-team-p01] Men, in particular, were eager and curious to see the women play.
[src:australia-women-s-national-cricket-team/australia-women-s-national-cricket-team-p01] The famous SCG barracker Yabba was quoted at the time: "The ladies are playing alright for me.
[src:australia-women-s-national-cricket-team/australia-women-s-national-cricket-team-p01] This is cricket, this is… Leave the girls alone!" Following two losses, Australia eked out a draw in the third Test at the MCG with the spin bowling duo of Anne Palmer and Peggy Antonio proving to be among the team's standout performers.
[src:australia-women-s-national-cricket-team/australia-women-s-national-cricket-team-p01] After raising their own funds to travel to the United Kingdom, the Australian women's team embarked on a maiden overseas voyage in 1937.
[src:australia-women-s-national-cricket-team/australia-women-s-national-cricket-team-p01] They proceeded to play 16 tour matches across England including three Tests—the first resulting in a narrow win which saw leg spinner Peggy Antonio dominate with the ball again while Kath Smith played a crucial all-round role.
[src:australia-women-s-national-cricket-team/australia-women-s-national-cricket-team-p01] With the series level at 1–1, the third Test was played at The Oval and attracted a crowd of over 6,000 people.
[src:australia-women-s-national-cricket-team/australia-women-s-national-cricket-team-p01] Soon after Australia's landmark tour, the momentum of the burgeoning women's game was halted by the events of World War II.
[src:australia-women-s-national-cricket-team/australia-women-s-national-cricket-team-p01] International cricket resumed toward the end of the 1947–48 season when Australia visited New Zealand for the first time, comprehensively defeating the hosts in the only Test of the tour.
[src:australia-women-s-national-cricket-team/australia-women-s-national-cricket-team-p01] The following summer, England returned to Australian shores and suffered their first series loss.
[src:australia-women-s-national-cricket-team/australia-women-s-national-cricket-team-p01] Having already affirmed herself as a star of the team with a ten-wicket haul and an innings of 90 against New Zealand, all-rounder Betty Wilson led Australia to a 186-run victory in the first Test of the 1948–49 series over England, claiming match figures of 9/62 as well as scoring a century.
[src:australia-women-s-national-cricket-team/australia-women-s-national-cricket-team-p01] Australia's 1951 tour of England included one of the closest finishes to a women's Test match in the 20th century.
[src:australia-women-s-national-cricket-team/australia-women-s-national-cricket-team-p01] The second Test, played in Worcester, was a tight battle as the Mollie Dive-led Australian team overcame a 39-run first innings deficit to successfully chase down a target of 160 on the final day of play with two wickets in hand.
[src:australia-women-s-national-cricket-team/australia-women-s-national-cricket-team-p01] Though Wilson contributed key runs and wickets as anticipated, it was ultimately the all-round performance of fast bowler Norma Whiteman (who finished the match with a defiant knock of 36 not out) which guided the team across the line.
[src:australia-women-s-national-cricket-team/australia-women-s-national-cricket-team-p01] Both players were also standouts in the Third test, though England nevertheless triumphed by 137 runs to end the three-match series at 1–1.
[src:australia-women-s-national-cricket-team/australia-women-s-national-cricket-team-p01] England's next tour of Australia produced several notable milestones, particularly during the first Test of the drawn 1957–58 series.
[src:australia-women-s-national-cricket-team/australia-women-s-national-cricket-team-p01] The match, played at the Junction Oval in Melbourne, marked the first time international cricket was broadcast on Australian television.
[src:australia-women-s-national-cricket-team/australia-women-s-national-cricket-team-p01] Betty Wilson was once again an inimitable force throughout the topsy-turvy contest, which ultimately ended in a draw, becoming the first player to take ten wickets and score a century in the same Test.
[src:australia-women-s-national-cricket-team/australia-women-s-national-cricket-team-p01] In another historic breakthrough, Faith Thomas made her debut in the match, becoming the first Indigenous person to represent Australia in any national sporting team.
[src:australia-women-s-national-cricket-team/australia-women-s-national-cricket-team-p01] Australia became a member of the International Women's Cricket Council (IWCC) at its inception in 1958, helping to form the governing body alongside England, the Netherlands, New Zealand and South Africa.
[src:australia-women-s-national-cricket-team/australia-women-s-national-cricket-team-p01] Lack of funds and low public interest throughout the 1960s caused the women's game, once again, to decline.
[src:australia-women-s-national-cricket-team/australia-women-s-national-cricket-team-p01] The on-field fortunes of the Australian team were simultaneously grim, as they finished the decade with a streak of eleven winless Test matches.
[src:australia-women-s-national-cricket-team/australia-women-s-national-cricket-team-p01] They were not successful in the early-1970s and had their first-ever Test mach loss to New Zealand.
[src:australia-women-s-national-cricket-team/australia-women-s-national-cricket-team-p01] Mary Allitt, who captained the national team for the 1963 tour of England, was awarded the Medal of the Order of Australia in June 2007.
[src:australia-women-s-national-cricket-team/australia-women-s-national-cricket-team-p01] One of the longest-serving players and administrators for women's cricket during this period was Lorna Thomas.
[src:australia-women-s-national-cricket-team/australia-women-s-national-cricket-team-p01] Retiring as a cricketer in the late 1950s, Thomas took up team management which included overseeing four tours abroad.
[src:australia-women-s-national-cricket-team/australia-women-s-national-cricket-team-p01] She retired from her position as manager of the New South Wales and Australian teams in the 1970s and was awarded an MBE for services to cricket.
[src:australia-women-s-national-cricket-team/australia-women-s-national-cricket-team-p01] The team attracted sponsors with the help of the first World Cup in 1973, which served as an introduction to the One Day International (ODI) format for women's cricket.
[src:australia-women-s-national-cricket-team/australia-women-s-national-cricket-team-p01] Australia finished the tournament as runners-up, losing to host nation England in the final.
[src:australia-women-s-national-cricket-team/australia-women-s-national-cricket-team-p01] The number of tours, both overseas and at home, increased soon thereafter.
[src:australia-women-s-national-cricket-team/australia-women-s-national-cricket-team-p01] Healthy finances allowed for investment in more suitable training and coaching, and these initiatives were vindicated with the team achieving global domination by the 1980s.
[src:australia-women-s-national-cricket-team/australia-women-s-national-cricket-team-p01] India paid a maiden visit in 1976–77, playing one Test match in Perth which resulted in Australia's first victory in the longest form of the game in nearly two decades, marking the beginning of the team's turnaround.
[src:australia-women-s-national-cricket-team/australia-women-s-national-cricket-team-p01] The following year, at the 1978 World Cup, Australia defeated England in the final to claim a breakthrough world championship.
[src:australia-women-s-national-cricket-team/australia-women-s-national-cricket-team-p01] Captain Margaret Jennings led the team in its triumphant campaign while Sharon Tredrea had a significant impact with bat and ball throughout the tournament which was held in India before crowds of up to 40,000 people.
[src:australia-women-s-national-cricket-team/australia-women-s-national-cricket-team-p01] Australia successfully defended their crown at the 1982 World Cup, held in New Zealand, by beating England in the final again.
[src:australia-women-s-national-cricket-team/australia-women-s-national-cricket-team-p01] Making their ODI debuts at the start of the tournament, batter Jill Kennare was the leading run-scorer for the team while Lyn Fullston took the most wickets of all players.
[src:australia-women-s-national-cricket-team/australia-women-s-national-cricket-team-p01] A dogged English team toured in 1984–85, pulling ahead early in a five-match Test series with a come-from-behind five-run win.
[src:australia-women-s-national-cricket-team/australia-women-s-national-cricket-team-p01] Not only did Australia respond resoundingly throughout the remainder of the summer to wrap up a 2–1 series victory, it would take more than 20 years to pass before England would record another Test match victory against their arch-rivals.
[src:australia-women-s-national-cricket-team/australia-women-s-national-cricket-team-p01] The fifth Test, played at Queen Elizabeth Oval, saw Australian captain Raelee Thompson—in her last season with the national team—take 5/33 on the first day of play to help set up a seven-wicket win for her country.
[src:australia-women-s-national-cricket-team/australia-women-s-national-cricket-team-p01] Jill Kennare and Denise Emerson were key performers with the bat throughout the series.
[src:australia-women-s-national-cricket-team/australia-women-s-national-cricket-team-p01] Australia completed a three-peat at the 1988 World Cup, defeating England in the final by eight wickets.
[src:australia-women-s-national-cricket-team/australia-women-s-national-cricket-team-p01] Despite recording the significant achievement on home soil at the Melbourne Cricket Ground, the match was played in front of just 3,000 people.
[src:australia-women-s-national-cricket-team/australia-women-s-national-cricket-team-p01] The decade-long global dominance of Australia had undoubtedly petered out by the 1993 World Cup when the team finished the group stage in third place, thus failing to qualify for the final.
[src:australia-women-s-national-cricket-team/australia-women-s-national-cricket-team-p01] The ultimate blow arguably occurred in their last pool match, suffering a brutal ten-wicket loss to New Zealand after being bowled out for 77.
[src:australia-women-s-national-cricket-team/australia-women-s-national-cricket-team-p01] In many respects, however, it also signified the start of an even more fruitful chapter in the team's history.
[src:australia-women-s-national-cricket-team/australia-women-s-national-cricket-team-p01] While several core group members, such as Lyn Larsen and Denise Annetts, retired from international cricket at the conclusion of the tournament or soon after, the next generation of stars had already begun to cement themselves at the top level—most famously Belinda Clark and Zoe Goss.
[src:australia-women-s-national-cricket-team/australia-women-s-national-cricket-team-p01] The following year, Goss also helped spark an unprecedented amount of attention around the women's game when she dismissed Brian Lara during a charity match at the Sydney Cricket Ground.
[src:australia-women-s-national-cricket-team/australia-women-s-national-cricket-team-p01] By 1995, with Clark having taken the reins of captaincy in the previous year, more cornerstones of a soon-to-be-ominous outfit had been added in batter Karen Rolton and coach John Harmer.
[src:australia-women-s-national-cricket-team/australia-women-s-national-cricket-team-p01] A biomechanics expert by trade, Harmer advocated for an exciting and enjoyable approach from his players: "After my first tour of New Zealand, I took them aside and said, *'This is so boring, sitting here, watching you lot play.
[src:australia-women-s-national-cricket-team/australia-women-s-national-cricket-team-p01] Make runs, take wickets, make the play and do it with a smile on your face.'*" In another shift for the game, the inaugural Women's National Cricket League (WNCL) season was held in the summer of 1996–97.
[src:australia-women-s-national-cricket-team/australia-women-s-national-cricket-team-p01] Australia completed one of their most devastating line-ups ever with the emergence of fast bowler Cathryn Fitzpatrick.
[src:australia-women-s-national-cricket-team/australia-women-s-national-cricket-team-p01] Having drifted in and out of the team during the early and mid 1990s, Fitzpatrick found the beginning of a rich and extensive vein of form just in time for the 1997 World Cup in India.
[src:australia-women-s-national-cricket-team/australia-women-s-national-cricket-team-p01] The Australians went through the group matches of the tournament undefeated, thrashing teams regardless of their historical strength on the world stage.
[src:australia-women-s-national-cricket-team/australia-women-s-national-cricket-team-p01] Not only did they defeat Denmark by 363 runs (which included a record innings of 229 not out by Belinda Clark) and bowled out Pakistan for 27, they also chased down totals set by England and South Africa with half-an-innings to spare.
[src:australia-women-s-national-cricket-team/australia-women-s-national-cricket-team-p01] The knockout stage proved to be more closely contested, though Australia nevertheless accounted for India and then New Zealand to reclaim the world championship.
[src:australia-women-s-national-cricket-team/australia-women-s-national-cricket-team-p01] The final, played at Eden Gardens, attracted an estimated crowd of at least 50–60,000 people.
[src:australia-women-s-national-cricket-team/australia-women-s-national-cricket-team-p01] Triumphant captain Clark has cited the scenes in the aftermath of the match as a career highlight: "Our victory lap is still etched in my memory, because we were being cheered like a home team.
[src:australia-women-s-national-cricket-team/australia-women-s-national-cricket-team-p01] The returning champions would be paraded around the SCG for a lap of honour during the 1997–98 New Year's Test, after which it was revealed they were going to have to pay for their trip.
[src:australia-women-s-national-cricket-team/australia-women-s-national-cricket-team-p01] So, this guy we'd never met wiped the debt for all of us.
[src:australia-women-s-national-cricket-team/australia-women-s-national-cricket-team-p01] The partnership between the Commonwealth Bank and women's cricket in Australia continues to this day.
[src:australia-women-s-national-cricket-team/australia-women-s-national-cricket-team-p01] She became the first woman in the world to take 100 ODI wickets while scoring 1,000 ODI runs.
[src:australia-women-s-national-cricket-team/australia-women-s-national-cricket-team-p01] 64 years into a fierce rivalry, Test series between Australia and England were officially designated as "the Women's Ashes" in 1998, derived from the name of the male equivalent.
[src:australia-women-s-national-cricket-team/australia-women-s-national-cricket-team-p01] Under the new moniker, the series immediately witnessed a new feat when Joanne Broadbent became the first Australia woman to score a Test double century.
[src:australia-women-s-national-cricket-team/australia-women-s-national-cricket-team-p01] Surprisingly, her innings of 200 lasted as a national team record for less than three years, surpassed by Michelle Goszko during the 2001 Women's Ashes.
[src:australia-women-s-national-cricket-team/australia-women-s-national-cricket-team-p01] In a further unexpected twist, Karen Rolton topped Goszko's benchmark of 204 merely two weeks later with a then-record score of 209 not out.
[src:australia-women-s-national-cricket-team/australia-women-s-national-cricket-team-p01] In late 2001, Women's Cricket Australia and the Australian Cricket Board made the decision to trial the integration of the two organisations, following similar recent initiatives by New Zealand Cricket and the England and Wales Cricket Board.
[src:australia-women-s-national-cricket-team/australia-women-s-national-cricket-team-p01] The merger was completed in 2003, resulting in the governing body now known as Cricket Australia, and has been regarded as a positive influence on women's cricket, providing more financial support and gathering more exposure for the sport.
[src:australia-women-s-national-cricket-team/australia-women-s-national-cricket-team-p01] Australia's next major triumph occurred at the 2005 World Cup in South Africa.
[src:australia-women-s-national-cricket-team/australia-women-s-national-cricket-team-p01] Having lost the final of the 2000 World Cup in a nail-biter against host team New Zealand, they proceeded to go undefeated in what was a successful campaign of redemption.
[src:australia-women-s-national-cricket-team/australia-women-s-national-cricket-team-p01] Shelley Nitschke and Lisa Sthalekar proved to be invaluable all-round additions to the team, while Karen Rolton became the first player to score a century in the knockout stage of a Women's Cricket World Cup by making 107 not out in the final against India.
[src:australia-women-s-national-cricket-team/australia-women-s-national-cricket-team-p01] The victory was among the last few appearances Belinda Clark made for Australia, retiring as the country's most prolific scorer in Women's ODIs later that year.
[src:australia-women-s-national-cricket-team/australia-women-s-national-cricket-team-p01] She went on to have arguably an even greater impact off the field, serving as an executive for Cricket Australia and helping to transform top-flight women's cricket from an amateur sport into a professional one.
[src:australia-women-s-national-cricket-team/australia-women-s-national-cricket-team-p01] Reiterating her distinguished standing in the game, the pre-eminent individual award in Australian women's cricket was named in Clark's honour in 2013.
[src:australia-women-s-national-cricket-team/australia-women-s-national-cricket-team-p01] The IWCC was officially integrated with the International Cricket Council (ICC) after the 2005 World Cup, promising to result in "greater media exposure and publicity" for the women's game than ever before.
[src:australia-women-s-national-cricket-team/australia-women-s-national-cricket-team-p01] Later that year, Australia's 15-match undefeated streak in Tests against England was broken when they lost by six wickets in Worcester.
[src:australia-women-s-national-cricket-team/australia-women-s-national-cricket-team-p01] The team's tour of the United Kingdom concluded in Taunton by playing in their first-ever Twenty20 International (T20I) fixture.
[src:australia-women-s-national-cricket-team/australia-women-s-national-cricket-team-p01] An innings of 96 not out by Karen Rolton helped the Australians to recover from 3/6, successfully chasing down a target of 153 with seven wickets in hand and 14 balls remaining.
[src:australia-women-s-national-cricket-team/australia-women-s-national-cricket-team-p01] Following the retirement of Belinda Clark, the unsurprising appointment of Karen Rolton as the new Australian captain occurred in early 2006.
[src:australia-women-s-national-cricket-team/australia-women-s-national-cricket-team-p01] Rolton's tenure oversaw a challenging transition period in the team's history as the careers of several players from the '90s zenith line-up came to a close—in particular, Cathryn Fitzpatrick made her last appearance for Australia in the final of the 2006–07 Quadrangular Series.
[src:australia-women-s-national-cricket-team/australia-women-s-national-cricket-team-p01] Fitzpatrick retired as the world's leading wicket-taker in Women's ODIs at the time and as her country's second-most prolific wicket-taker in Women's Tests behind Betty Wilson.
[src:australia-women-s-national-cricket-team/australia-women-s-national-cricket-team-p01] Searching to fill the immense void left by the departure of their premier fast bowler, selectors looked to the future by turning to a 16-year-old Ellyse Perry who would play her first ODI for the team in July 2007.
[src:australia-women-s-national-cricket-team/australia-women-s-national-cricket-team-p01] Australia hosted the 2009 World Cup and entered the tournament as favourites, but their performance fell well short of expectations and the team finished in fourth place.
[src:australia-women-s-national-cricket-team/australia-women-s-national-cricket-team-p01] Later in the year, at the inaugural Women's T20 World Cup held in England, they were defeated by the host nation in the semi-finals.
[src:australia-women-s-national-cricket-team/australia-women-s-national-cricket-team-p01] The following month, Karen Rolton made her last appearance for Australia during the only Test of the 2009 Women's Ashes.
[src:australia-women-s-national-cricket-team/australia-women-s-national-cricket-team-p01] After making a duck in the first innings, Rolton compiled 31 on the third day of play to become the only Australian woman to score 1,000 career runs in Test cricket.
[src:australia-women-s-national-cricket-team/australia-women-s-national-cricket-team-p01] The match ended in a draw despite a commanding innings of 139 by Jodie Fields, who had already assumed the captaincy from Rolton at the conclusion of the World Twenty20 tournament.
[src:australia-women-s-national-cricket-team/australia-women-s-national-cricket-team-p01] The fortunes of the team proceeded to turn around completely within ten months, culminating in triumph at the 2010 World Twenty20 tournament, held in the West Indies.
[src:australia-women-s-national-cricket-team/australia-women-s-national-cricket-team-p01] Australia defeated New Zealand in a thrilling final which was ultimately clinched by Ellyse Perry's fielding off her own bowling on the last delivery.
[src:australia-women-s-national-cricket-team/australia-women-s-national-cricket-team-p01] Opposition batter Sophie Devine struck a powerful straight drive back down the pitch, threatening to result in a match-tying four runs, but Perry instinctively stuck out her right foot and successfully stopped the ball from reaching the boundary.
[src:australia-women-s-national-cricket-team/australia-women-s-national-cricket-team-p01] Following Australia's maiden T20 world title, the prospects of the team became even brighter with Meg Lanning's inclusion during the summer of 2010–11.
[src:australia-women-s-national-cricket-team/australia-women-s-national-cricket-team-p01] A prodigious batting talent, Lanning became the country's youngest-ever centurion at 18 years and 288 days by scoring 104 against England in just her second ODI appearance.
[src:australia-women-s-national-cricket-team/australia-women-s-national-cricket-team-p01] In early 2012, Shelley Nitschke claimed a fourth-consecutive Belinda Clark Award (presented annually to the team's best player) soon after her retirement.
[src:australia-women-s-national-cricket-team/australia-women-s-national-cricket-team-p01] Then, in May, Cathryn Fitzpatrick was appointed as Australia's new head coach.
[src:australia-women-s-national-cricket-team/australia-women-s-national-cricket-team-p01] Fitzpatrick's stint at the helm was an extremely productive one which resulted in successful campaigns at the 2012 World Twenty20, the 2013 World Cup and the 2014 World Twenty20 tournaments.
[src:australia-women-s-national-cricket-team/australia-women-s-national-cricket-team-p01] Due to timely contributions with the bat, Jess Duffin garnered a reputation as a big game performer during the first two of the three events, earning Player of the Final honours on both occasions.
[src:australia-women-s-national-cricket-team/australia-women-s-national-cricket-team-p01] Meanwhile, Lisa Sthalekar capped off a stellar career with a fairytale ending at the 50-over championship in India, incidentally her country of birth.
[src:australia-women-s-national-cricket-team/australia-women-s-national-cricket-team-p01] Adopted at three weeks old by an American family, Sthalekar overcame unlikely odds to become the second woman to take 100 career ODI wickets for Australia.
[src:australia-women-s-national-cricket-team/australia-women-s-national-cricket-team-p01] She was also the first player in the world to achieve the double of 100 wickets and 1,000 runs in Women's ODIs.
[src:australia-women-s-national-cricket-team/australia-women-s-national-cricket-team-p01] Ahead of the 2013 Women's Ashes, the series structure was changed to a points-based system where matches would include ODIs and T20Is alongside the traditional Test format.
[src:australia-women-s-national-cricket-team/australia-women-s-national-cricket-team-p01] England would go on to win convincingly on home soil, and they would retain the trophy more controversially in their expedited Australian tour of 2013–14.
[src:australia-women-s-national-cricket-team/australia-women-s-national-cricket-team-p01] Despite winning both limited overs legs of the series, Australia still missed out on regaining the trophy due to losing the Test match, prompting a tweak to the points system for future editions.
[src:australia-women-s-national-cricket-team/australia-women-s-national-cricket-team-p01] In the latter portion of the series, an injured Jodie Fields was temporarily replaced as captain of the T20I team by 21-year-old Meg Lanning.
[src:australia-women-s-national-cricket-team/australia-women-s-national-cricket-team-p01] This replacement became permanent ahead of the T20 championship in 2014.
[src:australia-women-s-national-cricket-team/australia-women-s-national-cricket-team-p01] Along Australia's journey to achieving a World Twenty20 three-peat, Lanning would blast 126 runs against Ireland to set a new world record for the highest score in Women's T20Is.
[src:australia-women-s-national-cricket-team/australia-women-s-national-cricket-team-p01] Two months later, she was named captain of the national team in all three formats.
[src:australia-women-s-national-cricket-team/australia-women-s-national-cricket-team-p01] The appointment was reported as a "messy" handover from incumbent Fields who subsequently retired from international cricket despite urges from Australian selectors to reconsider.
[src:australia-women-s-national-cricket-team/australia-women-s-national-cricket-team-p01] More leadership changes soon followed as Cathryn Fitzpatrick decided to step down from her role as head coach in March 2015.
[src:australia-women-s-national-cricket-team/australia-women-s-national-cricket-team-p01] Ahead of the 2015 Women's Ashes, Matthew Mott was appointed as the team's new coach.
[src:australia-women-s-national-cricket-team/australia-women-s-national-cricket-team-p01] Australia won the series for the first time since the introduction of the points system, set up by an impressive Test win at the St Lawrence Ground.
[src:australia-women-s-national-cricket-team/australia-women-s-national-cricket-team-p01] Jess Jonassen starred with the bat while Ellyse Perry tore through the English line-up with the ball on the last day of play to help record a 161-run victory.
[src:australia-women-s-national-cricket-team/australia-women-s-national-cricket-team-p01] Back home, increased investment in the game began to take hold with the establishment of the Women's Big Bash League (WBBL).
[src:australia-women-s-national-cricket-team/australia-women-s-national-cricket-team-p01] Domestic women's T20 cricket in the country had previously been played via the Australian Women's Twenty20 Cup in which state squads were drawn from the seven-team WNCL competition.
[src:australia-women-s-national-cricket-team/australia-women-s-national-cricket-team-p01] Cricket Australia made the strategic decision to pivot and expand to a women's T20 equivalent of the eight-team model that had already been introduced to the men's game in the form of the Big Bash League (BBL), aiming to further heighten the profile and professionalism of elite-level female cricket.
[src:australia-women-s-national-cricket-team/australia-women-s-national-cricket-team-p01] Despite initial promising signs, the Mott–Lanning regime was soon on shaky ground after the team suffered shock defeats at two major events in as many years.
[src:australia-women-s-national-cricket-team/australia-women-s-national-cricket-team-p01] They lost a tightly contested final to the West Indies at the 2016 World Twenty20, and were then unceremoniously knocked out of the 2017 World Cup via a semi-final upset at the hands of India.
[src:australia-women-s-national-cricket-team/australia-women-s-national-cricket-team-p01] Australia's troubles were exacerbated by a shoulder injury to Lanning, who missed several games of the latter tournament and would undergo surgery soon after, sidelining her for six months.
[src:australia-women-s-national-cricket-team/australia-women-s-national-cricket-team-p01] With Lanning set to miss the 2017–18 Women's Ashes, Rachael Haynes stepped in as acting captain and the team retained the trophy via an inconsistent performance across the drawn series.
[src:australia-women-s-national-cricket-team/australia-women-s-national-cricket-team-p01] As part of the series, the first-ever women's day/night Test was held at North Sydney Oval, which ended in a draw.
[src:australia-women-s-national-cricket-team/australia-women-s-national-cricket-team-p01] The match was also particularly notable for Ellyse Perry's record-breaking innings of 213 not out, the highest score by an Australian in women's Tests.
[src:australia-women-s-national-cricket-team/australia-women-s-national-cricket-team-p01] Continuing to overhaul its approach to the women's game, Cricket Australia announced in June 2017 that the Southern Stars moniker—an official title of the team for several years—would be discontinued, thereby mirroring the nickname-free national men's team.
[src:australia-women-s-national-cricket-team/australia-women-s-national-cricket-team-p01] Then, in August, CA announced it would increase total female player payments from $7.5 million to $55.2 million, with the deal hailed as the biggest pay rise in the history of women's sport in Australia.
[src:australia-women-s-national-cricket-team/australia-women-s-national-cricket-team-p01] The on-field performance of the national team began to skyrocket in the wake of this watershed moment.
[src:australia-women-s-national-cricket-team/australia-women-s-national-cricket-team-p01] Additionally boosted by the return of their captain, Australia quickly embarked on an extended winning streak in ODI matches and T20I series.
[src:australia-women-s-national-cricket-team/australia-women-s-national-cricket-team-p01] They proceeded to win the 2018 World Twenty20, held in the West Indies, with a comprehensive defeat of England in the final which followed a dominant bowling and fielding display throughout the campaign as well as a Player of the Tournament performance by wicket-keeper Alyssa Healy.
[src:australia-women-s-national-cricket-team/australia-women-s-national-cricket-team-p01] The gap between the Australians and other cricketing nations appeared to have widened even further by the following year when they crushed England in the 2019 Women's Ashes.
[src:australia-women-s-national-cricket-team/australia-women-s-national-cricket-team-p01] Underlining the lopsided nature of the series, several individual records were achieved such as Ellyse Perry claiming the best-ever bowling figures by an Australian woman in ODIs, and Meg Lanning setting a new record for the highest score in a Women's T20I innings for the second time in her career.
[src:australia-women-s-national-cricket-team/australia-women-s-national-cricket-team-p01] Australia quickly turned their attention to the 2020 T20 World Cup, to be held on home soil, which was scheduled as a standalone event from the men's counterpart.
[src:australia-women-s-national-cricket-team/australia-women-s-national-cricket-team-p01] With the final fixtured at the Melbourne Cricket Ground, a media campaign urging fans to "Fill the MCG" ensued.
[src:australia-women-s-national-cricket-team/australia-women-s-national-cricket-team-p01] Although this generated a great deal of public interest in the campaign, it also placed a heavy weight of expectation on the team, given that they still had to win their way through to the last night of the tournament.
[src:australia-women-s-national-cricket-team/australia-women-s-national-cricket-team-p01] An early loss to India, a scare against underdog Sri Lanka, and a mounting list of injuries to key players ensured Australia's road to the final would not be easy.
[src:australia-women-s-national-cricket-team/australia-women-s-national-cricket-team-p01] At one stage, their fate rested entirely on favourable weather, with their must-win semi-final encounter at the SCG against South Africa threatening to be washed out.
[src:australia-women-s-national-cricket-team/australia-women-s-national-cricket-team-p01] The rain-reduced match, which was interrupted by several delays, eventually went ahead with Australia claiming a narrow victory and booking their place in the final.
[src:australia-women-s-national-cricket-team/australia-women-s-national-cricket-team-p01] Producing their best performance of the campaign in the championship decider, Australia defeated India by 85 runs to claim their first T20 World title on home soil.
[src:australia-women-s-national-cricket-team/australia-women-s-national-cricket-team-p01] Following an onslaught by the team's batters, the bowling unit led by Jess Jonassen and Megan Schutt restricted the opposition to a low total with the support of a flawless team effort in the field.
[src:australia-women-s-national-cricket-team/australia-women-s-national-cricket-team-p01] Beth Mooney's consistent run-compiling form earned her the Player of the Tournament award.
[src:australia-women-s-national-cricket-team/australia-women-s-national-cricket-team-p01] A record women's cricket crowd of 86,174 was in attendance for the final which media outlets described as a "landmark night" and a "game changer".
[src:australia-women-s-national-cricket-team/australia-women-s-national-cricket-team-p01] Later in the year, in acknowledgment of the history-making occasion, the national women's cricket team won The Don Award—widely considered the highest honour in Australian sport which is awarded to the athlete or team judged to have most inspired the nation through their performance and example.
[src:australia-women-s-national-cricket-team/australia-women-s-national-cricket-team-p01] Son of Sir Donald Bradman and namesake of The Don Award, John Bradman presented the award to the team, saying: "I have no doubt that my dad would have been absolutely thrilled with this result." Greta Bradman added: "I was there when the team won the T20 World Cup, and it was an emotional day.
[src:australia-women-s-national-cricket-team/australia-women-s-national-cricket-team-p01] After a hiatus caused by the COVID-19 pandemic, Australia returned to the international cricket stage by hosting New Zealand in September 2020.
[src:australia-women-s-national-cricket-team/australia-women-s-national-cricket-team-p01] During the tour, they recorded their 21st-consecutive ODI victory, equalling the world record set by the Ricky Ponting-led Australian men's team in 2003.
[src:australia-women-s-national-cricket-team/australia-women-s-national-cricket-team-p01] On 4 April 2021, they managed their 22nd-consecutive ODI victory (again beating New Zealand) to claim the record outright.
[src:australia-women-s-national-cricket-team/australia-women-s-national-cricket-team-p01] The streak extended to 26 victories before coming to an end via a two-wicket loss at Great Barrier Reef Arena in the last ODI of India's 2021–22 tour.
[src:australia-women-s-national-cricket-team/australia-women-s-national-cricket-team-p01] The only Test of the 2021–22 Women's Ashes, played at Manuka Oval, ended in a "dramatic draw" and was hailed for its "thrilling finish".
[src:australia-women-s-national-cricket-team/australia-women-s-national-cricket-team-p01] Seven Network analyst Lisa Sthalekar called it "the greatest Test match that I have been... involved in", while Fox Cricket commentator Isa Guha described it as "one of the greatest Test matches in Ashes history".
[src:australia-women-s-national-cricket-team/australia-women-s-national-cricket-team-p01] Having set England an unlikely target of 257 runs from 48 overs on the final day of play, Australia rallied late and took 6/26 in less than six overs to be one wicket away from sealing the win with a mere 13 balls remaining in the match.
[src:australia-women-s-national-cricket-team/australia-women-s-national-cricket-team-p01] The visitors managed to survive through to stumps, twelve runs short of a winning total, hence both teams falling just short of victory while also narrowly escaping defeat.
[src:australia-women-s-national-cricket-team/australia-women-s-national-cricket-team-p01] Australia proceeded to close out the series with a 12–4 score line, wrapping it up with three consecutive ODI wins and depriving England of a single victory for the entire tour.
[src:australia-women-s-national-cricket-team/australia-women-s-national-cricket-team-p01] In the following two months, Australia went through the 2022 Women's Cricket World Cup undefeated, culminating in a 71-run win against England at Hagley Oval.
[src:australia-women-s-national-cricket-team/australia-women-s-national-cricket-team-p01] With the team claiming a seventh 50-over title and winning 40 of 42 ODIs since their shock semi-final exit in 2017, *cricket.com.au*'s Laura Jolly said the triumph was "the crowning moment of a five-year journey of redemption".
[src:australia-women-s-national-cricket-team/australia-women-s-national-cricket-team-p01] In the championship decider, Alyssa Healy recorded the highest score in a World Cup final innings with 170 runs from 138 balls.
[src:australia-women-s-national-cricket-team/australia-women-s-national-cricket-team-p01] In May 2022, Matthew Mott departed to take on the head coach role of the England men's limited overs team.
[src:australia-women-s-national-cricket-team/australia-women-s-national-cricket-team-p01] Shelley Nitschke was subsequently elevated from her assistant coach position to interim head coach.
[src:australia-women-s-national-cricket-team/australia-women-s-national-cricket-team-p01] Australia then went undefeated throughout the T20 tournament at the 2022 Commonwealth Games, beating India in the final at Edgbaston by nine runs.
[src:australia-women-s-national-cricket-team/australia-women-s-national-cricket-team-p01] The following month, Nitschke was confirmed as the permanent head coach of the team.
[src:australia-women-s-national-cricket-team/australia-women-s-national-cricket-team-p01] Australia recorded 24 victories throughout the year—their only loss occurred in December during a five-match T20I tour of India, wherein the hosts won the second game of the series via a Super Over.
[src:australia-women-s-national-cricket-team/australia-women-s-national-cricket-team-p01] Australia completed another hat-trick of world titles by defeating South Africa in the championship decider of the 2023 ICC Women's T20 World Cup, played at Newlands Cricket Ground.
[src:australia-women-s-national-cricket-team/australia-women-s-national-cricket-team-p01] Beth Mooney was named Player of the Final (an honour she also earned six months earlier at the Commonwealth Games), while Ashleigh Gardner was named Player of the Tournament for her all-round performance.
[src:australia-women-s-national-cricket-team/australia-women-s-national-cricket-team-p01] For most of the 20th century, the typical playing attire for female cricketers included skirts or culottes worn with long socks.
[src:australia-women-s-national-cricket-team/australia-women-s-national-cricket-team-p01] This deviation from the men's game, in which trousers were standard issue, ended in 1997.
[src:australia-women-s-national-cricket-team/australia-women-s-national-cricket-team-p01] The existence and subsequent extinction of the now-infamous culottes, paired with the players previously having to pay out of their own pocket for the unfortunate fashion trend, has been cited as a symbol of the shift from the amateur to professional era in women's cricket.
[src:australia-women-s-national-cricket-team/australia-women-s-national-cricket-team-p01] An additional small difference can be spotted on the coat of arms (which appears on the baggy green among other items of apparel), wherein the colours of the scroll and the "Australia" motto are reversed from red and gold for the men's team to gold and red for the women's team.
[src:australia-women-s-national-cricket-team/australia-women-s-national-cricket-team-p01] In February 2020, for the first time, the team wore an Indigenous-themed uniform design (featuring artwork created by Aboriginal artists) in a T20I match against England.
[src:australia-women-s-national-cricket-team/australia-women-s-national-cricket-team-p01] The team song is sung by the players after every victory.
[src:australia-women-s-national-cricket-team/australia-women-s-national-cricket-team-p01] Unlike the men's team, which sings Under the Southern Cross I Stand, the women sing their own song to the tune of the Notre Dame Victory March.
[src:australia-women-s-national-cricket-team/australia-women-s-national-cricket-team-p01] Commonly known players include Meg Lanning, Belinda Clark, Cathryn Fitzpatrick, and Ellyse Perry.
[src:australia-women-s-national-cricket-team/australia-women-s-national-cricket-team-p01] Clark and Fitzpatrick are both in the ICC hall of fame, while Lanning and Clark captained Australia.
[src:australia-women-s-national-cricket-team/australia-women-s-national-cricket-team-p01] Perry is a Double international, having represented Australia in both cricket and soccer.
[src:australia-women-s-national-cricket-team/australia-women-s-national-cricket-team-p01] The current national captain of Australia is Sophie Molineux and the current vice captains of Australia are Tahlia McGrath and Ashleigh Gardner, but they have been many appointed captains for Australia over the years.
[src:australia-women-s-national-cricket-team/australia-women-s-national-cricket-team-p01] A minimum of 18 players are offered a Cricket Australia women's contract each year.
[src:australia-women-s-national-cricket-team/australia-women-s-national-cricket-team-p01] The program is conducted over a twelve-month period in which the athletes attend approximately three camps per year at the National Cricket Centre and undergo specialist training sessions within their home state.
[src:australia-women-s-national-cricket-team/australia-women-s-national-cricket-team-p01] Individual programs are developed for each squad member by the women's team head coach in consultation with the state coaches and the player.
[src:australia-women-s-national-cricket-team/australia-women-s-national-cricket-team-p01] The player progress is monitored via testing, coach state visits, training diaries and communication with the athlete's coaches (state and satellite) by the head coach with assistance from the Australian team support staff and relevant state coach.
[src:australia-women-s-national-cricket-team/australia-women-s-national-cricket-team-p01] The table below lists the players awarded a national women's team contract with Cricket Australia on 8 April 2026, as well as any active player to make an appearance for the team within the last 12 months.
[src:australia-women-s-national-cricket-team/australia-women-s-national-cricket-team-p01] Players not named on the initial list can be upgraded during the following twelve-month period by accruing twelve national team selection points to earn a contract—appearances at Test level are worth four points, while ODIs and T20Is are worth two each.
